						<p class="faqquestion">{{{__ 'PLACES TO VISIT'}}}</p>
						<p>{{{__ 'You can easily spend a week in and around Santa Fe. Here are some of our favorite in-town activities:'}}}</p>
						<ul>
							<li><strong>{{{__ 'Santa Fe Plaza'}}}</strong>: {{{__ 'Located downtown, Santa Fe\'s Spanish Colonial plaza was established in 1609. The Native artisans who sell silver, turquoise, and crafts on the north end of the plaza all come from local Pueblos, and all their crafts are handmade. The plaza is home to St. Francis Cathedral and the Palace of the Governors, a museum that\'s also the oldest continuously used building in the United States.'}}}</li>
							<li><a href="https://www.okeeffemuseum.org/" target="_blank"><strong>{{{__ 'The Georgia O\'Keeffe Museum'}}}</strong></a>: {{{__ 'Right off the plaza, this museum is small and lovely, and dedicated to the artist\'s legacy and American Modernism (O\'Keeffe spent the latter half of her life in New Mexico).'}}}</li>
							<li><a href="http://museumhill.net/" target="_blank"><strong>Museum Hill</strong></a>: {{{__ 'Located about two miles from the plaza, Museum Hill is home to four excellent museums &emdash; the Museum of Indian Arts &amp; Culture, the Museum of International Folk Art, the Wheelwright Museum of the American Indian, and the Museum of Spanish Colonial Art. We love their botanical garden, too.'}}}</li>
							<li><a href="http://www.canyonroadarts.com/canyon-road-galleries/" target="_blank"><strong>{{{__ 'Canyon Road Galleries'}}}</strong></a>: {{{__ 'Aside from New York, Santa Fe has more art galleries than any city in the United States. Canyon Road is only a half-mile long and boasts more than one hundred galleries, boutiques, and restaurants.'}}}</li>
							<li><a href="https://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/american_latino_heritage/barrio_de_analco_historic_district.html" target="_blank"><strong>{{{__ 'Barrio de Analco Historic District'}}}</strong></a> {{{__ '(now East de Vargas Street): Just steps away from Canyon Road, and one of the country\'s oldest continuously inhabited streets.'}}}</li>
							<li><a href="http://www.matteucci.com/" target="_blank"><strong>{{{__ 'Nedra Matteucci Gallery'}}}</strong></a>: {{{__ 'One of the best galleries in Santa Fe, and one of our favorites; don\'t miss the beautiful sculpture garden. And it\'s across the street from Kakawa Chocolate House!'}}}</li>
							<li><a href="https://www.railyardsantafe.com/" target="_blank"><strong>Railyard District</strong></a>: {{{__ 'Just outside of downtown, the Railyard District is filled with art spaces, cafes, and shopping. Check out the Santa Fe Farmers\' Market or stop by Second Street Brewery for a beer and one of their tasty green chile cheeseburgers.'}}}</li>
						</ul><br/>

						<p class="faqquestion">{{{__ 'NEAR-TOWN ACTIVITIES'}}}</p>
						<ul>
							<li><strong>{{{__ 'Hiking'}}}</strong>: {{{__ 'There are dozens of day-hike options in and around Santa Fe. For a wonderful day hike, head to <a href="https://www.rei.com/passport/Kasha-Katuwe-Tent-Rocks-National-Monument" target="_blank">Kasha-Katuwe Tent Rocks National Monument</a>, 50 minutes southwest of Santa Fe. There you can do an easy 1.2-mile hike or a moderate-to-challenging 3-mile hike on <a href="http://www.alltrails.com/trail/us/new-mexico/tent-rocks-canyon-trails" target="_blank">Tent Rocks Trail</a>, which offers gorgeous views of striated rock formations, the famous hoodoos (tent rocks), the Sangre de Cristo, Jemez, and Sandia mountains, and the Rio Grande Valley. Wherever you hike, be sure to carry water and bring layers; the weather can change rapidly as you ascend and descend.'}}}</li>
							<li><a href="https://tenthousandwaves.com/" target="_blank"><strong>Ten Thousand Waves</strong></a>: {{{__ 'If you make a pastime of pampering, head to this beautiful Japanese-style spa with forest-view hot tubs and Asian-style massages. The spa is 10 miles outside of Santa Fe and located on a mountain overlooking the city. You can enjoy a communal tub or sauna, rent a private tub, book a massage or facial, and dine at their James Beard-nominated Japanese restaurant, Izanami. Book at least a few weeks in advance, as spots tend to fill up quickly.'}}}</li>
						</ul><br/>
						<img src="/img/kasha-katuwe-tent-rocks.jpg" alt="Kasha-Katuwe Tent Rocks" style="display: block; max-width: 400px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" /><br /><br />

						<p class="faqquestion">{{{__ 'DAY OR OVERNIGHT TRIPS'}}}</p>
						<ul>
							<li><a href="http://www.ojospa.com/" target="_blank"><strong>Ojo Caliente</strong></a>: {{{__ 'Sarah and her sister Amy stayed here way back in 1998! A mineral hot springs and hotel, Ojo Caliente is lovely for a day trip or overnight stay. You can float in the hot springs, enjoy a massage or mud bath, dine at their restaurant, and stay overnight in either their newer accommodations or historic 1916 hotel. Ojo Caliente is about an hour\'s drive north of Santa Fe.</li>
							<li><strong>The High Road from Santa Fe to Taos</strong>: This route offers a combination of New Mexicana and panoramic views. The trip takes about two hours without stopping, but it\'s worth visiting several towns along the way where time has stood still. These include'}}}:
								<ul>
									<li><strong>Chimayó</strong>, {{{__ 'famous for its Sanctuario de Chimayó (a pilgrimage site for many Hispanic Catholics) and traditional weaving galleries (visit Trujillo\'s)'}}}.</li>
									<li><strong>Truchas</strong>, {{{__ 'two towns up the road, has been settled by many artists and is home to several galleries.'}}}</li>
									<li><strong>Peñasco</strong>, {{{__ 'home to the fabulous Sugar Nymph\'s Bistro, started by a couple who left the San Francisco food scene to pursue dreams of a small-town cafe. Make time for lunch or cake!'}}}</li>
									<li><strong>Taos Pueblo</strong>: {{{__ 'When you get to Taos, be sure to visit the Pueblo, the only living Native American community designated both a World Heritage Site by UNESCO and a National Historic Landmark. The multi-storied adobe buildings have been continuously inhabited for over 1,000 years. When you\'re done exploring Taos, you can halve your return journey by taking the Low Road, along the Rio Grande River, back to Santa Fe.'}}}</li>
								</ul>
							<li><a href="https://www.nps.gov/band/index.htm" target="_blank"><strong>{{{__ 'Bandelier National Monument'}}}</strong></a>: {{{__ 'About an hour\'s drive west of Santa Fe, this impressive Monument contains 23,000 acres of backcountry wilderness, waterfalls, and wildlife. It\'s best known for the remarkable petroglyphs carved into the nooks and crevices of the canyon wall above the dwellings by ancestral Puebloans.'}}}</li>
							<li><strong>Abiquiú</strong>: {{{__ 'Georgia O\'Keeffe\'s famed ranch in Abiquiú, which served as the setting for many of her paintings, can be toured by <a href="https://connect.okeeffemuseum.org/abiquiu-tours" target="_blank">appointment</a> on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, and Saturdays. If you\'re interested in visiting, we recommend booking well ahead of time. Check out the nearby <a href="http://www.abiquiuinn.com/" target="_blank">Abiquiú Inn</a> for a meal or overnight stay. Abiquiú is about an hour\'s drive north of Santa Fe.'}}}</li>
						</ul>
